The total sum of the lengths in the question statement is written as a sum of terms, so by linearity of addition we can find each term and then add them all up. In the text I have used <i>text tags</i> for input. First we let $O$ be the center of the circle. Then note that all symmetries of the figure that can be obtained by rotating the figure about $O$ are rigid transformations. In particular, we have that since $\triangle OAB$ is congruent to $\triangle OBC$ (because $OA=OB=OC$), we have that $\angle AOB=\angle BOC$. Thus every angle of $\triangle OAC$ is a multiple of $30^{\circ}$. Taking any two points on one of the 12 sides let there be $x$ points in the interior and let $\overline{PQ}$ be the line segment with the greater number of points in its interior. <i>Here categorial counting is used because we can find the lengths of segments with integer count of points in the interior at first glance.</i> Thus we have that $|AQ|$ is congruent to $6$, $|AP|>|AO|=|AP|+6$ (since $|PO|+|AO|=|AP|+6>12$) hence so is $|AO|$. Thus the other 2 sides are $6\sqrt{3}$ and $12$ by symmetry (and the 2 triangles are right triangles that we easily find via 30-60-90 triangles). Thus our sum ending up equals the sum of these lengths multiplied by 12 because there are 12 sides plus twice the sum of all of these lengths because each diagonal has been counted (note we count twice so the last terms are twice). Thus our total amount is
